S. 1. 6. 104 n. naves : either the rostra of captured ships, or perhaps even ships themselves drawn in a triumphal procession by means of machinery. 193. ebur, ie.. statues of ivory and gold: Livy speaks of tusks carried in procession in the triumph over Antiochus (37. 59 tulit in triumpho . . . eburneos dentes M CCXXXI ) but these would not be suited for a display on the stage. Corinthus: not restricted to vessels of Corinthian bronze, though doubtless including these, but all the spoils of Corinth, and also probably a painting of the city. So Porphyrion quia imagines eius oppidi fabricantur, ut in trium- phali pompa transire possint. Cp.
